# ESLint Code Checking Standards

> **Related Rules**: See [Code Formatting](./formatting.mdc), [Type Safety](./typescript.mdc), [Code Quality](./code-quality.mdc), [Git Workflow](./git-workflow.mdc)

## Basic Principles

- All TypeScript and HTML files must pass ESLint checks
- Must run `yarn lint` or `npm run lint` before commit
- Use `--cache` option to improve check speed
- Use `--fix` option to automatically fix fixable issues

## Execution Methods

```bash
# Check all files
yarn lint

# Check TypeScript only
yarn lint:ts

# Auto fix issues
npx eslint --cache --fix
```

## Configuration Requirements

- Use `@typescript-eslint/parser` to parse TypeScript
- Use `@typescript-eslint/eslint-plugin` to provide TypeScript rules
- Use `eslint-plugin-import` to check import order
- Use `eslint-plugin-unused-imports` to detect unused imports
- Use `eslint-plugin-jsdoc` to check JSDoc comments
- Use `eslint-plugin-prefer-arrow` to prefer arrow functions
- Use `eslint-config-prettier` to avoid conflicts with Prettier (see [Code Formatting](./formatting.mdc))

## Key Rules

- Prohibit using `any` type (unless necessary and explicitly marked) (see [Type Safety](./typescript.mdc))
- Enforce arrow functions (when applicable)
- Check unused imports and variables
- Enforce JSDoc comments (for public APIs)
- Check import order and grouping

## Git Hooks Integration

- Automatically check before commit through `lint-staged` (see [Git Workflow](./git-workflow.mdc))
- Only check modified files to improve speed
- Block commit when checks fail

